File: Undertakers lift the remains of a COVID-19 patient at a mortuary. AFP/Marco Longari JOHANNESBURG - COVID-19 fatalities could be much higher than official figures suggest. The South African Medical Research Council (SAMRC) says there were more than 145,000 excess natural deaths over the past ten months. READ: COVID-19 in SA: Western Cape prepares for third wave They were recorded between May and February. The SAMRC does not give details on the cause of these extra deaths but estimates that between 85 and 95 percent are attributable to COVID-19. READ: Health workers celebrate after sharp drop in COVID-19 cases So far, the health ministry has recorded over 1.5 million coronavirus cases, of which more than 50,000 have been fatal. Experts predict a third infection resurge by the start of the southern hemisphere winter from late May. - Additional reporting AFP